    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-08-02T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-08-02T13:00:00-05:00" n="551"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d551">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Council/8–249: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        United States Deputy for Austria at the Council of Foreign Ministers</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_RS1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reber</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-08-02T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 2, 1949—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2715.<note n="1" xml:id="d551fn1">Repeated to Vienna as 841.</note> Audel 113. Re
                        <gloss target="#t_Delaus1">Delau</gloss> 198 July 29<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d551fn2">Not printed.</note> we consider informal discussions by one
                    Western Deputy with <persName corresp="#p_ZGN1">Zarubin</persName> desirable in
                    endeavor to ascertain possibility of settlement at this time. We are in full
                    concurrence with your view that Western position on Art. 35 should not be
                    sacrificed as there is no positive indication that Sovs will agree other issues
                    if claims are satisfied. Dept hopes that you can convince your Brit colleague
                    that any compromise which would increase Aust obligation beyond point envisaged
                    in Paris Agreement would seriously endanger Western policy in Aust in future. We
                    do not consider that further concessions are called for on our part since
                    Western states demonstrated their willingness to compromise by meeting Sov
                    position on Ger assets at Paris conference.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
